  <div class="pixelate">
    <h1>Ever wondered if the person you like also likes you back?</h1>
    <p>Pairlet can let you know when there is mutual interest.<br />
      Connect your Twitter and Facebook accounts, then start adding your Flirts.</p>

    <% if !user_signed_in? %>
    <div class="signup">
      <h2>Try it, sign in with:</h2>
      <p>
        <%= link_to raw('<i class="icon-twitter"></i> with Twitter'), user_omniauth_authorize_path(:twitter), :class => 'btn btn-twitter' %>
        <%= link_to raw('<i class="icon-facebook"></i> with Facebook'), user_omniauth_authorize_path(:facebook), :class => 'btn btn-facebook' %>
      </p>
    </div>
    <% end %>
  </div>

  <div class="container-fluid how">
    <div class="row-fluid">
      <div class="span4">
        <h3>How it works:</h3>
        <p>
          <h5>1. Sign up and connect your Twitter &amp; Facebook accounts.</h5>
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="span4">
        <p style="padding-top:21px;"><h5>2. Add flirts using their Twitter or Facebook usernames.</h5></p>
      </div>
      <div class="span4">
        <p style="padding-top:21px;"><h5>3. Let Pairlet handle the rest.</h5></p>
        
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="how-explain span8 offset2">
     <p style="padding-top:50px;">The people you add as "Flirts" won't know you flirted them, and you won't know when someone flirted you either. Unless... Unless you both flirt each other.</p>
     <p>Pairlet will let you know and notify you via email so you can get in touch.</p>
     <p>No hard feelings, no rejections, no awkward moments. Happy flirting.</p>
  
     <p class="disclosure">
      <small><em>Pairlet only stores your Facebook and Twitter usernames, as well as your email address for notifications. <u>Nothing</u> else. <br />
      You can delete (destroy) your account at any time.</em></small>
    </p>
  </div>
